Passwords are often not read from STDIN. Instead, they are read directly from the [psuedoterminal or PTY](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pseudoterminal). This means it&#39;s reading from the controlling terminal program, not from STDIN. This is an obsolete security measure meant to make automating filling in passwords harder. To a cracker it&#39;s a speed bump, but it&#39;s very inconvenient to everyone else.

Here&#39;s a simple program echoing input from the PTY.

```Perl
open my $fh, &quot;/dev/tty&quot; or die $!;
print while &lt;$fh&gt;;
```

This program will not see input piped to STDIN. It will only see what you type on the terminal.

There are various ways to talk to a program&#39;s PTY. One of the most powerful is to use [Expect](https://metacpan.org/pod/Expect).

```Perl
#!/usr/bin/env perl
  
use Expect;

my $exp = Expect-&gt;spawn(&quot;perl tty.pl&quot;) or die $!;
$exp-&gt;send(&quot;test\n&quot;);
$exp-&gt;soft_close();
```

